TY  - JOUR
T1  - Approximation Procedures for the One-Warehouse Multi-Retailer System
AU  - Lu, Lu
AU  - Posner, Marc E.
Y1  - 1994/10/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.40.10.1305
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.40.10.1305
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1305
EP  - 1316
VL  - 40
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Two heuristic procedures for a one-warehouse multi-retailer system are developed. Based on the accuracy desired, the first heuristic evaluates a specified number of points. The relative error is within a bound that approaches 1/(√2 ln 2) ? 1 ≈ 2.014%. The complexity of the heuristic is O(n) for a fixed number of evaluations. Although our bound only approaches the one of Roundy (1985), when only a small number of points are evaluated, our method is faster. We show that the bound for our procedure and two bounds proposed by Roundy (1985) are tight. The second heuristic pertains to a class of polities called stationary interval policies. For this class of policies, we develop a fully polynomial-time approximation scheme where the relative error is within ε > 0, and the computational effort increases as a linear function of 1/√ε. Computational experiments show that these heuristics perform well in practice.
AB  - Two heuristic procedures for a one-warehouse multi-retailer system are developed. Based on the accuracy desired, the first heuristic evaluates a specified number of points. The relative error is within a bound that approaches 1/(√2 ln 2) ? 1 ≈ 2.014%. The complexity of the heuristic is O(n) for a fixed number of evaluations. Although our bound only approaches the one of Roundy (1985), when only a small number of points are evaluated, our method is faster. We show that the bound for our procedure and two bounds proposed by Roundy (1985) are tight. The second heuristic pertains to a class of polities called stationary interval policies. For this class of policies, we develop a fully polynomial-time approximation scheme where the relative error is within ε > 0, and the computational effort increases as a linear function of 1/√ε. Computational experiments show that these heuristics perform well in practice.
