TY  - JOUR
T1  - Note: The Impact of Leadtime and Years of Competitive Rivalry on Pioneer Market Share Advantages
AU  - Huff, Lenard C.
AU  - Robinson, William T.
Y1  - 1994/10/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.40.10.1370
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.40.10.1370
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1370
EP  - 1377
VL  - 40
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Research has established that for surviving brands, market pioneers have a higher average market share than later entrants. By moving first, market pioneers often develop sustainable market share advantages. Longer leadtime, which is the time between entries, should increase these pioneer advantages. Using two leadtime measures, this prediction is supported across 34 categories of frequently purchased consumer goods. Increasing the years of competitive rivalry should help a later entrant slowly reduct the pioneer's market share advantage. After more than two decades in the market, second entants have eliminated the pioneer's market share advantage, but third and later entrants continue to trail the pioneer.
